text: Meet Kimberle Crenshaw, a pioneering civil rights advocate, professor, and leading critical race theory scholar known for not only working at the intersection of race and gender, but for coining the term #intersectionality to call attention to how systems of oppression overlap to create distinct experiences for those with multiple identity categories. Among her many contributions is co-founding and founding and leading African American Policy Forum, an intersectional think tank behind campaigns such as #SayHerName, which calls attention to police violence against Black women and girls. #BlackHerstoryMonth

AfroMundo Festival: Beyond the Pale Literary Event Sunday, April 17, 2022 3 pm A literary reading and discourse with Puerto Rican and Dominican authors Mayra Santos Febres, Eleuterio Santiago D√≠az and Loida Maritza P√©rez. ‚ÄúBeyond the pale‚Äù is a British colonial phrase for those who, for living beyond borders and boundaries, actual or imagined, were considered beyond the rule of law and of accepted social norms. The phrase further suggests ‚Äúotherness‚Äù and has since taken on racial connotations, as in not white; dull, savage, incompetent, dark, backwards; heathen; diabolic, transgressor, hence illegal. Authors will read works and discuss the stigmas associated with those in the Caribbean who practice Afro traditions. Free community event #NHCCNM #NMCulture #Arte #AfroMundo

1 in 5 incarcerated people in the entire world are in the United States. We're either a uniquely criminal society or we lock up way too many people. Judging by this chart, which shows that people who are incarcerated tend to be the poorest of the poor, I'd say it's the latter. We need to invest in education, not more incarceration.

The Hillel Leadership Institute with Stanford Hillel is back and our next talk is coming up next week! Join Berkeley Hillel and Stanford Hillel on Tuesday, March 8th at 6pm on Zoom for "What's On An Interviewer's Mind? Finding and Securing the Job for You: Stories on Hiring in Venture Capital and Startups" We'll hear from two panelists who work in different industries, each of whom will provide the group with insights and advice on applying to jobs and internships at startups and venture capital firms. The panelists will be: Mike Splain is a DevOps engineer and Manages the Cloud Infrastructure Engineering team at Sonos. Previously, he worked at PayPal and was an early member of a number of startups. Mike is also a maintainer on open source software called Kubernetes and has presented at numerous tech conferences. Gaby Goldberg is an investor at The Chernin Group, where she focuses on the firm's investments at the intersection of consumer and crypto. She previously worked on the early-stage consumer team at Bessemer Venture Partners and Chapter One. RSVP for this event by emailing Micah Lesch at mlesch@berkeleyhillel.org. #zoom #venturecapital #cloudinfrastructure #leadership #institute #talk #job #stories #story #industry #startup #advice #jobs #development

Today, on National Black HIV/AIDS Awareness Day, Advocates for Youth announced the release of a new engaging HIV/STI prevention program: "Get Your Life." Following a pilot program that included over 200 Black and Latine youth, "Get Your Life" is a valuable HIV/STI prevention tool made by and for Black and Latino Young men. The program is a seven-session group-based HIV prevention facilitation guide designed to inspire conversations about HIV, STIs, relationships, and identities through a culturally responsive and sex-positive lens. We‚Äôre so excited this resource exists and want to remind you that we‚Äôre here to help! Reach out for resources and access free HIV and STI testing Monday-Thursday next door, provided by Birmingham AIDS Outreach.

Welcome to our second day of highlighting various organization across the country combating anti-LGBTQ+ laws. Today we will be highlighting our first Florida organization, QLatinx. ‚ÄúQLatinx was founded in response to the mass shooting and act of hate that occurred on June 12, 2016 at Pulse nightclub in Orlando, FL, during the LGBTQ+ establishment‚Äôs Latinx themed night, that robbed our community of 49 lives and left many more physically and psychologically wounded. QLatinx brought together members of the local community directly and deeply impacted by this tragedy to build a supportive infrastructure, address inequity, and promote inclusionary practices for local leadership and partnering agencies.‚Äù They seek to center and empower the most marginalized members of our community, establish affirming and supportive healing spaces, build a strong and united community, and work towards a society free of fear, violence, and hate. You can help them further their mission by making a donation, becoming a monthly sustainer, advocating in workspaces, and matching contributions. All this information can be found on their website at https://www.qlatinx.org/support. Thank you QLatinx for providing safe spaces and for honoring the legacy of those lives lost in 2016.

The AAARCC was my lift off into Asian and Asian American "sociology" in real time. I've always been interested in Asian American studies, especially how our Asian background affects the way we interact with others alike and unlike us. It gives a place for you to not feel like you're learning, but the moment you step into the AAARCC, there's always something new to encounter. I, as a pre-Pharmacy major, love to learn and the AAARCC gives the perfect outlet of something that is the exact opposite of my current studies. The reading program introduced me to more people who were just as interested in learning about Asian and Asian American culture and I still say hello and talk to them today. It's a welcoming environment to those who want to learn about Asian/Asian American culture, no matter what background you come from. Dr. Pam Sari and Manabu Taketani are always looking to help support and uplift causes big and small on campus. By allowing so many different Asian Student Organizations on campus to host events (aside from the many they host on their own), it's become a second home for many, and I hope that more see the AAARCC the same way I do. On Tuesday March 9th at 6PM join us in our next AAARCC Virtual Film Series. We will watch Confetti (2021), followed by a recorded Q&A with Producer/Director Ann Hu. Post-Movie discussion will be led by Dr. Margaret Tillman (Director, Purdue Asian Studies Program) and Lisa Yates (Access Consultant, Purdue Disability Resource Center). Written, produced, and directed by award-winning New York-based filmmaker ANN HU, based on her own experiences, CONFETTI looks at the often-silent struggles faced by so many immigrant families. Featuring an affecting performance by Zhu Zhu, a steely and strong-willed turn by Amy Irving, and a delightful debut from young Harmonie He, CONFETTI shows that amongst a deluge of challenges, a sprinkling of hope, heart, and determination can help make sense of a confusing world and our place in it. The Supreme Court announced its ruling in Loving v. Virginia on June 12th, 1967‚Ä¶ a unanimous decision finding Virginia‚Äôs international marriage law a violation to the 14th Amendment. It overturned the Lovings‚Äô criminal conviction for getting married, despite being different races. This case also did the same in 16 other states, and set a precedent for same-sex marriage laws in the future. The last state to accept this ruling was Alabama, occuring not too long ago in 2000. Although we may think this history is far in our past, this reminds us that it‚Äôs not. Today, June 12th is known as ‚ÄúLoving Day‚Äù and can be celebrated in multiracial families!! #blackhistoryisamericanhistory

January 27, the anniversary of the liberation of Auschwitz-Birkenau in 1945, is commemorated as International Holocaust Remembrance Day. We honor the memory of the 6 million Jews and millions of others, including Roma, LGBTQ+ people, and people with disabilities, who were killed by the Nazis. But what did your average Virginian understand about the Holocaust during WWII? We look to the coverage of Nazi persecution in Virginia newspapers during the 1930s and 1940s to find out. In partnership with the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum, the Library of Virginia offers four ‚Äúresearch sprints‚Äù into our newspaper collection: https://www.handsonrva.org/opportunity/a0C5c00000Kttr3EAB:=:https://www.handsonrva.org/opportunity/a0C5c00000Kttr3EAB?lang=1

Black communities have made great progress in reducing HIV. Yet to truly #StopHIVTogether, we must confront issues such as racism, discrimination, and mistrust in the health care system that prevent many Black people from accessing HIV testing, prevention, and treatment.

On February 7, we recognize National Black HIV/AIDS Awareness Day (NBHAAD), a day dedicated to raising awareness of the disproportionate impact of HIV on Black Americans and the importance of increasing access to HIV education, testing, treatment, and prevention services. On this day, and throughout the year, it is important to acknowledge and address the social and structural determinants of health that drive the HIV-related health disparities experienced by Black communities.

Celebrate #maple season with us by learning some fun facts about maple (and taking note of one not-so-fun fact). Did you know... - Sugar maples are the state tree of New York! - New York is home to the largest resource of tappable maple trees in the United States. - New York State ranks second in the nation for maple production, producing 804,000 GALLONS of maple syrup in 2020! - The alternation of both freezing and thawing temperatures is necessary to create the pressure which causes the sap to flow when sugar maple trees are tapped. Sap runs best when temperatures drop below freezing at night and rise into the 40s during the day, which is very common in March. That's why March is maple month! And a not-so-fun fact: ALL maple trees, including our precious syrup makers, are prone to devastation by the Asian Longhorn Beetle (ALB). Show your support to your local maple producers this season by visiting their sugarhouses for tours, tastings, and demonstrations throughout the state - AND show your support for their trees by reporting any signs of damage from Asian Longhorn Beetle to our ALB HOTLINE at (866) 265-0301. #invasivespecies #maplemonth #nysmaple #asianlonghornbeetle NYS Maple NYS Department of Environmental Conservation New York Invasive Species Research Institute

The Hispanic Business Student Association (HBSA) at San Diego State University is pleased to announce its Annual High School Conference in collaboration with Alpha Pi Sigma taking place on Saturday, April 16th, 2022 from 10:00am to 4:00pm at SDSU. HBSA‚Äôs mission for our Annual High School Conference is to bring diverse students onto a college campus and instill higher education into their minds. We hope to invoke professionalism and leadership development that will help students succeed throughout their academic and individual careers. We would like to extend an invitation to join us for our FREE High School Conference. It will be a great opportunity for students to learn about San Diego State University and what it has to offer. This conference will include guest speakers, workshops, a campus tour, and a complimentary lunch! The workshops we will be hosting include Financial Aid, College Readiness, Career Success, and Community/Wellness. All available to you for FREE! In addition, We are pleased to announce that this year we will be offering two scholarships, open to any grade level, each worth $200. To register: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSczIx0NjK9Mb1gju5Z6YAcEQYqJaYpAWHtJ-VD7nkUgta89yQ/viewform Please feel free to contact hbsa.hs.conference@gmail.com for any questions or concerns.

Temperatures will be mild today due to an air mass that has been heavily modified by downslope flow in the lee of the Rockies. In Nebraska highs will be 15 to 25 degrees above seasonal averages. Not quite as warm in Iowa, only around 10 degrees above seasonal averages, due to lingering snowpack.
Snowfall map and totals from January 15.

Temperatures will moderate today, especially over portions of eastern Nebraska where the mercury will bounce back into the 40s. Winds will strengthen from the northwest by afternoon with gusts of 25 to 35 mph.
The 6 to 10 Day Temperature Outlook suggests warmer than average temperatures in the Plains next week.

IBX CEO Greg Deavens joined Global Citizen for a news conference about the upcoming Martin Luther King, Jr. Day of Service. This year's observance includes a focus on public health efforts like COVID-19 vaccinations. "COVID-19 has made it crystal clear that health equity is still an important battleground in the fight for racial equality and equity. Dr. King knew this more than 50 years ago. He believed that 'of all forms of discrimination and inequities, injustice of health is the most shocking and inhuman,'" Deavens remarked. IBX is proud to follow Dr. King's lead in the betterment of our city, the region, and the nation. For more about the event on January 17, visit https://volunteer.globalcitizen365.org/
